{
  "script": [
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "Hello everyone! Today we have Dr. Alex, a renowned astrophysicist joining us to discuss black holes."
    },
    {
      "character": "Dr. Alex",
      "line": "Hi Jane, thanks for having me."
    },
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "So let's dive right in. What exactly is a black hole?"
    },
    {
      "character": "Dr. Alex",
      "line": "Well, imagine a star so massive, when it dies, not even light can escape its gravitational pull."
    },
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "Wow, that's crazy! Now, I've heard they're like cosmic vacuum cleaners?"
    },
    {
      "character": "Dr. Alex",
      "line": "In a way, yes. They can suck in matter from nearby stars and planets."
    },
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "That sounds terrifying! Are there any black holes close to us?"
    },
    {
      "character": "Dr. Alex",
      "line": "Actually, our solar system has a close brush with one. It's called Sagittarius A*."
    },
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "So how do we study them if nothing can escape?"
    },
    {
      "character": "Dr. Alex",
      "line": "We use a technique called gravitational lensing. Massive objects like black holes warp space, bending light around them."
    },
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "This has been fascinating, Dr. Alex. How can listeners learn more?"
    },
    {
      "character": "Dr. Alex",
      "line": "Check out NASA's black hole webpage. It's a great starting point."
    },
    {
      "character": "Jane",
      "line": "Well folks, today we've learned that black holes are like cosmic vacuums, and one is lurking not too far from us!"
    }
  ]
}
